      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i've tried the private talks but it's not really working. they both just play the victim and say the other person started it. it feels like they're just being petty for the sake of it, like they're enjoying the power struggle. is there a specific way to frame the conversation so they stop acting so immaturely during the meetings?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It's like trying to get a stubborn goblin to stop playing tricks on you - they can be quite resistant to change. In this case, you might need to take a more direct approach. Consider framing the conversation as a team issue, rather than a personal attack on either of them. You could say something like, \"I've noticed that during our syncs, there's been a lot of tension and it's affecting the team's productivity. I want to make sure we're all working together effectively. Can we find a way to communicate more respectfully and professionally, even when we disagree?\" This approach focuses on the impact of their behavior, rather than attacking them individually.",
